U.S. engineers have photographed water droplets using a high-speed camera mounted directly above the real liquid beads to investigate how they behave.

They found that a moving - or 'oscillated - drop of water can form over 30 different shapes, including a 'standing wave pattern' and an 'azimuthal wave pattern'

Experts took the photographs by shining a light through mesh holes and photographing the light that reflected off the drop's surface as it moved.

