'We created an imaging platform where we could look at the drop from the top, to enable us to see the characteristic shapes better than anyone has before.'

The imaging platform, which Chang has named the 'Omniview' because of the different angles at which the droplet can be observed, consists of a glass slide, the droplet sitting on top and a 50-micron-square metal mesh, like a window screen, underneath.

A light is shined through the mesh holes and deflection of the drop's surface refracts the light, which is seen as a deformation of the mesh and captured by a high-speed camera.

