The researchers mechanically oscillated the drops at varying frequencies to observe and record their movements.

The oscillation can be likened to when a violin string is plucked. Certain natural frequencies correspond to a given length of string, the same way certain frequencies correspond to the shape of a drop of a specific size.

The researchers created a detailed table of droplet shapes according to frequency, as well as comparing these results to previous theoretical predictions involving the dynamics of oscillating droplets.

